Gosh Darn, you Guys, <br>
Left the place for a day or so and you've posted over 30 notes. Won't even visit #126 sounds like an echo and a good departure, would have packed his bags for him if he had asked me to.<br><br>
All I did here was get on spatz case for dumping his load on my response to SW about divine intervention in Vietnam. Seems like when I open up with some serious stuff it really irritates him, like the tread on lost innocence, really bothered him then above on Divine Intervention. I will no longer bother with  him, gave him all the chances in the world. Barry c. Spatz, I will tell you this, I've been threaten by some powerful individuals in my past, your treats don't mean anything. Compared to others you're small stuff and you'll have to get in line with the Bloods and Cribs as well as some of East LA gang members some in and some out of  the brig. When you've faced death as often as I have, you only fear God, and you fear him only for not doing what you know is right. <br><br>
Art, <br>
I'm like you, but I not only liked war, I loved war. Loved the power and destruction in my hands, but like you I hated it and saw it as my way of ending the pain and suffering. Much like giving a citation on the force. In order to catch a traffic violator for speeding, I had to break the speed limit myself. Wrecked nine patrol cars and screwed many gun barrels into some bad dudes ears, I loved it then and even now with the freedom I found after I left the force. <br><br>
M24, I was born when Israel became a nation and when it came of age for war so did I. Have always felt a connection for some reason. A lot of things happened in Nam on the force and else where in my life and I have always felt alone, have often stood alone against great odds. Raised in the city dump, when my dad was killed by a drunk driver when I was only four. But have never felt like I was some bad dude, just fortunate, god's hand has always been there. Have also felt that if not by the grace of God after VN, I would have ended up on skid row. There has always been a line red line between goodness and hell, between darkness and light, peace and war, friendship and animosity, hatred and love, clamor and silence, black and white, peace and war. Sometimes it was hard to tell what was sane and what was insane. <br><br>
I remember a Marine freaking out in the middle of the rice paddy, bullets flying all over the place and he goes nuts, lays ther cuddled up in the fetal position crying like a baby. I couldn't understand it, but then who was the crazy one. I was standing over him trying to get him up while the bullets were flying all over the place. Another time a Marine left his unopened can of coke on the top of the amtract, when we were ambushed. Bullets flying like crazy, grenades exploding, tanks firing, RPG's going off, 60's blasting away and this Marine looks up at his coke and we all knew what he was going to do, I think we all though about it. He wasn't about to let some gook shoot a hole through it., so he made a mad dash for the coke, grabs it and brings it back, we all cheered for him, we were young, I was 19 and naďve. <br><br>
When Israel became a Nation I was born when it went to war so did I, somehow I've always felt a connection there. That's why I shared my story about God's intervention in my life, felt a connection somehow. I not only believe I do not have PTSD, but that I have also obtained closure in many areas of my Vietnam experiences and that has brought me great peace, but I hunger for others to find it as well. <br>
Have never joined a vet organization but now I feel like I want to especially after reading what you all have posted over the past few months. The V V A seems like the only place that I feel like I could belong to. <br>

